segments.text: If you're just sitting on the sidelines taking it easy, then I'm not going to deal with you.
The most perilous thing in the world is to be the point man, because you don't know whether what you're doing is right or wrong.
You can only be guided by your conscience, your intelligence, and what you feel is right.
But because you are doing something, because there are dynamics there, you're going to make mistakes.
Screwing up should never be a reason to fire somebody.
Somebody screws up is because they're doing something.
The guy who never does anything wrong is probably not doing anything.
So people who tell me that the government should be doing this, the government's had 10 years to do it.
A million times zero is still zero.
That's exactly what the government's got.
We need dynamics.
We need a change.
And I think that the only way to get the issue resolved is to provide a catalyst that will break the diplomatic logjam.
They're trying to do something that's impossible right now.
They've come to loggerheads with the communists for all the reasons I've already said.
There needs to be a catalyst there.
I intend to provide that catalyst.
And then I'm going to get out of it.
I tell the government every time I talk to them, I don't like doing your job for you.
I'm not being paid for it.
If you'll just start doing it, I'll be glad to get out of it, and I know you'll be glad to have me out.
But throughout American history, any time that there has been a vacuum of government, it's been filled by private citizenry.
An example?

not directly related but partially related is the watergate the executive branch would not examine itself so what happened the legislative branch filled that vacuum and required the executive branch to police itself back in king george's time there was a vacuum of government a few men who were determined
to see right and justice done had guts enough to sign the Declaration of Independence.
I don't know who'd sign it today.
Everybody wants some damn lawyer.
You know, it's okay if you want to check with King George.
So I hope that in the history of the United States from this day forward, any time there is a dearth of government action that some, that's what we're about, is freedom.
is some individual will find courage enough to withstand the slings and arrows of criticism that will be hurled at him, because that's exactly what happens.
The first thing that they do, go back through history and do some homework.
Anytime someone has tried to go against the status quo, the first thing they do is try to discredit him.
Failing that, then they'll begin to marshal all of the bureaucracy.
No man has been successful

standing against the bureaucracy i don't know whether i will be or not and when i say that i have to caveat it because you see who is our consumer advocate yeah nadir but he wasn't fighting the u.s bureaucracy he was fighting general motors at that time martin luther king was successful but uh jesus christ was successful
Look what they tried to do to him.
They nailed him to the cross.
Everybody said he was a nut.
Anytime.
You know, you go back through history, it doesn't mean that they were wrong.
It means they happened for a short time to be a majority of one.
As long as you're dealing with truth and reality, those two things can withstand the test of time.
So I know I'm on perfect ground.
One, I have the secret to life.
I earned it through learning about death.
I earned it up on that mountain where I got some truths.
I know about life.
I'm fearless right now because I don't have to worry.
I know what comes next.
I know that I'm right because what I'm dealing with is truth.
I wouldn't be doing if I didn't know it wasn't true.
So in the end, I know all the critics, just like the critics of the Washington Post when they started talking about Watergate.
I know what the result's going to be.
All I got to do is stand back and just watch it happen.
And so that's why I don't get concerned about critics.
Can you explain how Velvet Hammer came about and why did it fail?
Yes.
Velvet Hammer didn't fail.
It never got out of the jungles of Florida.
But it came about because, again, I was asked to retire, and I did in 1979.
By 1980, we had developed information that included satellite photos of American prison camp in Laos.
We went to Florida to train to rescue those prisoners.
President Reagan won the election.
He was briefed on the situation, and like Admiral Tuttle told me, he was the man Jerry Tuttle was responsible for this mission in the Pentagon out of DIA then.
He said, quote, the president's excited about this.
We're going to make the rescue using federal troops.
We don't need you no more, Bo.
You can go home.
I knew it wasn't ever going to happen, and so I begged him.
He said, Bo, I got them by the balls on this thing.
They can't turn it around.
We're going to rescue those prisoners.
So I disbanded the troops in Florida.
We went home Easter in 1981.
The raid never came off.
When Admiral Tuttle called me May 21, 1981, at my home in Los Angeles, he said, Beau, tomorrow the Washington Post is going to break a story that says that the CIA sent Lao mercenaries
looking for prisoners and found none.
And I said, Admiral, are you telling me that they've turned the planes around?
Because I use the analogy of the Bay of Pigs, and he says, yes, it's off.
So then that's what happened with Velvet Hammer.
What about Grand Eagle?
Grand Eagle was a product of the ISA.
ISA, Carter did one thing.
As far as I know, that was good.
He created, in the wake of the Iranian debacle,
a special intelligence organization that Congress didn't know about called ISA.
Its purpose was to rescue and do special missions that was outside the congressional oversight.
And oversight's a damn good word to use with respect to Congress.
But if you wanted to do a clandestine operation, you had to go through seven subcommittees of Congress.
Some of them are pink old commie faggots.
We know that because we have films of them committing fellatio with people in the Longworth building in the men's room.
They're all kind of fruits and nuts in Congress.
So it is insane to think you can conduct clandestine operations by getting Congress approval.
So ISA was created specifically to work for the president to do this kind of thing.
Theoretically, it was wonderful.
But in reality, it had no fangs because as soon as Velvet Hammer went down, ISA told me, Bo, we've picked this thing up now.
We're going to do it.
And that was Grand Eagle.
It never got across the creek.
I was supposed to have gone across the Mekong River to document Americans in captivity and bring one back if possible.
It never got off of the drawing boards because DIA challenged ISA.
Theoretically, ISA should have prevailed.

But in reality, because bureaucratically it was safer to keep the POW issue in the filing cabinets of the Pentagon, because if I'd have gone across the creek, there's a goddamn good chance that they would have had to dealt with something in three dimension instead of two-dimensional paperwork.
So ISA failed.
As a result, ISA became exposed.
And there was a big article in the paper about how the president was just now
but too late, beginning to get a handle on some of the secret intelligence activities that were going on.
So that's what happened with Grand Eagle.
It wasn't very grand because it never got out of the United States, and it certainly wasn't an eagle.
I called it Boheka, which meant bend over, here it comes again.
That's exactly what it turned out to be.
What do you think were the political reasons for Kissinger's refusal to accept the list of POWs from the Cambodian?
Good reasons.
Good, perfectly wonderful political reasons.
One, his marching orders were to get out expeditiously with honor.
If he would have dealt with a Lao, it would have opened up a whole new dimension to the war because we had forever denied that we were in there.
My helicopters used to be shot down over there, and every time they were, I used to have to say when we couldn't recover them that I was off course, that I didn't know where I was.
That's crap.
We were conducting the war in Laos for good reason, because that's where the enemy was.
But if Kissinger would have accepted the POW list, he would have had to have opened up that whole new arena.
It would have lengthened the time that we could have gotten out with honor.
It would have meant reparations for the Laos because we had destroyed property, resources, and people.
And we would have had to have dealt with that.
And it would have meant a larger economic package.
It would have meant negotiations.
It would have meant exposure because American activists would have said, what do you mean Laos?
What are we doing fighting the war in Laos?
We never heard about that.
And so for those reasons,
And I fault him for this because if Kissinger would have been a good human being, he would have weighed his conscience against the good of the nation.
And you see, in the end, maybe in the short run, the good of the nation was to say, go away, Laos, we're not going to talk to you.
But damn it, in the long run, what is this country about if it's not about the humans that make it up?
So when he let those brave soldiers drop between the cracks, he wasn't right.
Even though
He was following his boss's orders, which was get out with honor now.
So for political expediency, he signed those men's death warrants in many cases.
Have any of them been recovered?
No.
The Lao have never turned over a prisoner of war.
Do we have proof that there actually are some prison awards that are aligned in Los Angeles?
What about the satellite photograph?
The only reason the satellite picture was taken was because the patrol said, hey, we saw 30 Americans precisely here at Namarat.
And then the satellite was positioned, and bingo, there's Fort Apache.
That's what Chairman Dornan called it because he got privileged all the information.
In addition, there are the hundreds of refugee reports.
The evidence is as clear as a nose on our face.
If we will open our political eyes, we will see that in others.
The best analogy I can give is Denison Lane, spokesman for the Pentagon, said this about yellow rain.
With so many people saying it's so, it must be so.
And everybody believed that.
There were only about 10 people talking about yellow rain in those days.
I used Denison Lane's words.
With so many people saying it's so, it must be so.
Because there have been almost 3,000 reports
from natives of Southeast Asia talking about Americans in captivity.
670, more than, firsthand eyewitness reports, satellite photographs, intelligence chiefs that say, yes, with all that I know, I must say that we left those prisoners behind.
Silver stars given out for people that were left behind.
There's no question about it.
Not because I say so.
The Laos say, we're not saying we don't have the prisoners of war.
We're saying Laos is a big country, very poor.
You help us, we'll go look.
The Vietnamese don't say they don't have prisoners of war.
They say that they are holding American criminals, common criminals, but that they have no right to be identified because we have no diplomatic relationship with them.
The president says it's top national priority, but yet
A deputy assistant secretary is the highest-ranking U.S. official to ever go to Vietnam and talk about this since Henry Kissinger left 10 years ago.
So if that's the kind of top national priority it is, I think it's bullshit.
And that's why I'm willing to act as a vigilante if I have to, even though I don't advocate vigilantism in this country.
Why do you think those countries are still holding the POWs there?
I mean, what benefit do they have?
They represent billions of dollars in economic aid.
And because they're humanitarian.
If they weren't humanitarian, they would have killed them a long time ago when it became obvious the United States wasn't going to pay off.
But you see, in the beginning, the Vietnamese thought they were going to negotiate with Henry Kissinger.
And they said, here's our parcel of POWs.
We were going to, over five years, give them $3.5 billion.
And they were going to continue to give us POWs in that exchange.
We didn't give them a dime because even though Nixon signed the agreement, Congress didn't ratify it.
So we tricked them.
Ha-ha, we tricked ourselves because they had planned on parceling out POWs in return for that economic aid.
Secondly, Nixon said, if you violate the Paris Peace Accord, I'm going to start bombing Hanoi again.
So Hanoi had good reason to hold those prisoners as an umbrella of security.
Nixon got washed away at Watergate.
As a result, Ford had no fangs.
There was no threat.
What do you do with those POWs?
Thirdly, there was a POW who, like Jimmy Ray, because he violated certain laws that they had, they said, we are changing your category from prisoner of war to common criminal.
You will never go home.
So for those good reasons, and like the Lao, if you were a Lao villager,

and a fighter bomber were to come over and drop bombs and some of those bombs killed your villagers destroyed your homes and resources and that fighter bomber were to crash and you were to capture the pilot what would you think of him would you think that he was a war hero to be treated with respect as the red baron might have created one of our aces no you are a criminal
You're going to be held as a criminal because you've taken our lives, you've destroyed our property and our resources.
And we're going to hold you in prison because you're not even at war with this country.

And until we recognize the fact that there are as many bomb holes as in Laos as there is in Vietnam and deal with the truth as it is real, those guys, the Lao, have every reason to hold them as Americans.
And so that's some of the reasons why they've kept them.
and why they're still keeping them.
One, what do you do with them?
Go out and shoot them all?
They are not that kind of a people.
Secondly, they still represent the potential for whatever 1983 dollars would be.
It was 3.5 in 1973.
But a lot of that stuff has escalated 10 times.
And some of it's only escalated half, maybe, in the inflation of 73 and 83.
But certainly it represents probably $10 billion today.
How are we going to drive that kind of a budget wedge into an already strained economy?
So you understand why the president has a problem with that.
he's hoping that somebody like me will go over there and bring one back so that on human rights basis we can get them back for nothing.
Because if he has to drive that $10 billion wedge, it has to go to all the unpopularity of opening up the wound of war.
What politician is going to survive that?
It's an unpopular cause.
It's going to bring great scrutiny down on him.
If you were a political advisor, you'd probably tell the president to stay away from it.
So for all those reasons, you would be right, but you would be wrong.
for the deep reason that it is not right.
Morally, we're obligated to bring those lives home because they're American citizens and they have a right
to life as we know it in this country.
And the worst thing that can happen to a warrior is to die alone in the hands of his enemies.
And that's what's going to happen to those guys.
It's happening even today.
Give me some information about your current new operation, Lazarus, and what direction do you think it's going to take?
Well, Lazarus is finished.
Lazarus was in three phases.
It began in September.
of 1982 when we went to Thailand to solidify intelligence.
That was phase one.
Phase two is when we crossed into Laos twice to evaluate guerrilla organizations who purportedly could do the job, but I hadn't seen it proven on the ground.
Phase three was called Lazarus Omega where we were going to make the rescue.
We were betrayed and all that resulted since then.
There is a new operation we are calling it Phoenix because from those ashes we are going to rise stronger and hopefully invincible this time to finish the job.
Phoenix is prepared.
We are waiting.
We have one more step.
Nothing else remains to be done.
Everything is set.
The last step I will make will be to bring the prisoner home.
And the mechanism is set, and we're just simply waiting for it to work.
What time frame are we looking at?
Well, I'm not going to be specific for intelligence reasons, but it's difficult to move during the monsoon season.
The rain makes movement, food, communications.
It degrades everything.
Last year we launched in November because that's when the rain stops.
Okay, and my last question is, what is it in you?
You sort of answered it before, but I want to hear more specifically.
What is it in you that keeps you searching for these aliens?
Just because I know they're there, I know they're alive, and who else is going to do it if I don't?
Admiral Inman of the CIA said, Bo, if I were to tell you that the CIA will do everything we possibly can to get these Americans home, will you stop?
I said, no, sir, because I know he's full of crap.
They are politically controlled.
They're not only going to do in their bureaucracy.
Who are they?
They are little bureaucrats in a building at Langley.
They need someone who has been across the river, who has been there to see it.
Martin Luther King said, I've been to the mountains.
Damn it, I've been across the Mekong.
I know that they're there.
I know the CIA.
I know the DIA.
I know the President of the United States doesn't really know what they're talking about when he says we're doing all possible.
What does that mean, all possible?
If it's top national priority, why don't we fly the POW flag every day?
If it's top national priority, why isn't the vice president over talking to the Vietnamese right now?
So I know they're full of crap.
Those are sweet words like check is in the mail and a lot of other things.
And sweet words aren't going to get those Americans home.
It's going to take direct action, straight line type action.
And it takes intensive action.
You can't just do it on a part-time basis.
Put it in my inbox, I'll get to it later.
It has to be worked 24 hours a day because it is one hell of a project.
This nation has not rescued American prisoners of war since January 1945.
We failed at Sante, we failed at Mayaguez, we failed in Iran, and we sure didn't succeed in the Bay of Pigs.
We traded some of our prisoners back for tractors.
That's a measure of success.
So we haven't done anything right in this country since World War II.
And the reason, as I think, because we have been working on a double standard.
The U.S. government looks at what is best for the nation, and it quantifies it with respect to economics and politics.
but yet the soldier is expected to perform based on what's good for the nation, duty, honor, country, and not what is in his own best interest.
What if the soldier, when asked to go to Latin America, said, well, let me see, is it in my best personal interest?
I'm getting paid $550.
I may get my ass shot off.
It isn't.
I'm not going.
Well, that's exactly what the nation is doing.
It's saying, how much is it going to cost us?
How many votes is this going to be?
Politically, how sensitive is this?
It's not worth it.
We won't do it.
So if the individual reacted the way the nation's reacting, we'd give a war and nobody would go.
And maybe that'd be the right thing to do.
I don't know.
The nation is our mother.
The government is our mother.
Nobody likes to hear their mother called a whore, even if it's the truth.
I want the government to look good.
Unfortunately, it is tough to get them to commit
And I have told them, I'm going to give you all the discredit you deserve if you don't help us in this endeavor.
Because it's very dangerous.
I'm going to be really angry if something happens to me or that American PW and we're coming back across the river this time because the bureaucracy didn't want to get involved.
And I intend to jam it right down their throat.
I don't like the idea.
And in the end, I may renege and let them say it was all their idea.
I don't know.
Time will tell that.
But I'm doing it because if I don't, who will?
And there are a lot of critics, but not very many people willing to get into the arena.
Okay.
Thank you.
All right.
I appreciate it.
